{"key":"processedPost-10969452","value":{"id":10969452,"first":10968441,"last":10973214,"when":1251689011,"utime":"08/31/09 06:23 AM","content":"For cubensis, coir and horse manure are about equal.&nbsp; This has been borne out by thousands of grows over the last five years since everyone thought I must have bumped my head when I said coir works as a substrate.&nbsp; Until then, the prevailing wisdom was that coir has 'no nutes' just like some people still think about vermiculite, which is another myth I'm trying to put to rest.<br /><br />Cost is relative to location.&nbsp; I live in the countryside, with horses in my yard.&nbsp; For me, horse manure is free for the taking without ever starting the truck.&nbsp; For city people, a local pet store might be an easier choice to get coir than driving 30 miles to get 'free' manure.<br />RR","title":"Re: HPOO owns Coir hands down"}}